-- Palm Oil Advances for Third Day as Malaysian Exports Gain, Stockpiles Drop
-- Pratik Parija
-- 2010-07-12T11:25:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/palm-oil-advances-for-third-day-as-malaysian-exports-gain-stockpiles-drop.html

          
          
             Palm oil advanced for a third day
after shipments from Malaysia, the second-biggest producer,
increased and stockpiles of the commodity dropped.  
 Futures for delivery in September rose 1.7 percent to 2,340
ringgit ($730) a metric ton on the Malaysia Derivatives Exchange.
The price climbed as high as 2,341 ringgit intraday.  
 Shipments from Malaysia gained 8.8 percent in the first 10
days of July, compared with the previous-month period, Societe
Generale de Surveillance, an independent cargo surveyor, said
today. A total of 460,343 tons were tracked, SGS said. Exports
were 423,199 tons during the same period in June. Overseas sales
climbed 9 percent in the first 10 days of the month, rival firm
Intertek said July 10.  
 Palm oil stockpiles in Malaysia declined 7.1 percent in
June from May. Inventory of the edible oil, used in food and
biofuel, fell to 1,451,434 tons, the nationâ€™s Palm Oil Board
said today. Output rose 2.5 percent to 1,420,062 tons, while
exports gained 5.5 percent to 1,440,884 tons.  
